bead.description:
Add the federation layer that takes an external identity (Tailscale tailnet handle today, OIDC/email tomorrow) and resolves it to a first-class axon User with an idempotent auto-provision. This is the non-JWT arm of the auth pipeline. The JWT arm is done (B1). The middleware wiring that dispatches between the two arms depends on D1 (path router) — this bead stays focused on the federation primitive and its storage/test surface.

## What is in this bead

1. Storage adapter extension: one new trait method that atomically upserts a user_identities row and its parent users row, returning the User. Implemented on all three backends (memory, sqlite, postgres) using the ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING pattern from ADR-018 §6.

2. A federation helper module in axon-server that takes a Tailscale whois response (reuse TailscaleWhoisResponse from existing crates/axon-server/src/auth.rs) and resolves it to a User via the new storage method.

3. Tests proving the 64-way concurrent race converges on one users row, and that adding a second provider for the same human keeps the users row stable while adding a user_identities row.

## What is NOT in this bead (defer to follow-up beads)

- Middleware wiring of the Tailscale path into verify_request — depends on D1 (path router) to know which tenant the URL names; that's a later bead.
- PROP-011 Tailscale↔JWT equivalence property test — same reason; requires full middleware. I'll file a follow-up bead after D1 lands.
- INV-021 axon-sim workload — axon-sim integration is bigger than this federation primitive; defer to a dedicated simulation bead.
- OIDC provider support — this bead only wires Tailscale as a provider, but the storage layer and the trait method are provider-agnostic so OIDC falls out naturally in a later bead.
- Role resolution / grants synthesis — that depends on B4 (tenant_users + role ceiling helper). B3's output is just a resolved User; the caller will look up membership and build grants separately.

## Scope — exactly what to add

### 1. Extend crates/axon-storage/src/adapter.rs StorageAdapter trait

Add one new method alongside the B1 auth methods:

    /// Upsert a (provider, external_id) -> User mapping atomically.
    ///
    /// On first call for a given (provider, external_id) pair this creates a
    /// new users row and a new user_identities row pointing at it. On
    /// subsequent calls it returns the existing user. The method MUST be
    /// concurrency-safe: N parallel calls with the same (provider, external_id)
    /// must converge on exactly one users row and one user_identities row.
    ///
    /// ADR-018 §6 specifies the SQL pattern:
    ///   INSERT INTO users (id, display_name, email?, created_at_ms)
    ///   VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
    ///   INSERT INTO user_identities (provider, external_id, user_id)
    ///   VALUES (?, ?, ?) ON CONFLICT (provider, external_id) DO NOTHING;
    ///   SELECT user_id FROM user_identities
    ///   WHERE provider = ? AND external_id = ?;
    ///
    /// Returns the user that now owns this identity (whether freshly created
    /// or pre-existing). Returns Err only on real SQL errors, not on
    /// 'already exists' races.
    fn upsert_user_identity(
        &self,
        provider: &str,
        external_id: &str,
        display_name: &str,
        email: Option<&str>,
    ) -> Result<User, AxonError> {
        let _ = (provider, external_id, display_name, email);
        Err(AxonError::Internal("upsert_user_identity not supported by this adapter".into()))
    }

The default is an error so adapters that haven't been taught about auth schema don't silently succeed.

### 2. Implement in all three storage backends

- crates/axon-storage/src/memory.rs — use an in-memory HashMap<(String, String), UserId> keyed on (provider, external_id), wrapped in the adapter's existing lock/mutex scheme. The first insert wins; subsequent inserts return the existing user.

- crates/axon-storage/src/sqlite.rs — use rusqlite with the exact SQL from ADR-018 §6 above. The first two INSERTs use ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING; the SELECT returns whichever user_id won the race. Wrap the three statements in a single transaction.

- crates/axon-storage/src/postgres.rs — same pattern with tokio_postgres. The three statements go in a BEGIN/COMMIT block.

### 3. Add federation helper: crates/axon-server/src/federation.rs

A new module:

    //! Identity federation: maps external identities (Tailscale, OIDC, email)
    //! to first-class Axon users via the storage adapter's upsert path.

    use std::sync::Arc;
    use axon_core::auth::User;
    use axon_core::error::AxonError;
    use axon_storage::StorageAdapter;

    use crate::auth::TailscaleWhoisResponse;  // already exists in crates/axon-server/src/auth.rs

