    /// on first seen.
    ///
    /// The external_id is the LoginName (email) when present, else the
    /// ComputedName (node name fallback), matching the existing behavior of
    /// crates/axon-server/src/auth.rs Identity resolution.
    pub fn resolve_tailscale_identity(
        whois: &TailscaleWhoisResponse,
        storage: &dyn StorageAdapter,
    ) -> Result<User, AxonError> {
        // extract external_id, display_name, email from whois
        // call storage.upsert_user_identity("tailscale", &external_id, &display_name, email.as_deref())
        // return the User
    }

Re-export resolve_tailscale_identity from crates/axon-server/src/lib.rs via the federation module.

### 4. Tests: crates/axon-server/tests/federation_test.rs

New test file. Use the memory storage adapter + apply_auth_migrations_sqlite-equivalent setup (if the memory adapter needs a migration step) to set up a fresh tenancy DB.

Test cases:

a) upsert_fresh_creates_user_and_identity — call upsert_user_identity once, assert users has 1 row, user_identities has 1 row, returned user's display_name matches.

b) upsert_same_identity_is_idempotent — call upsert_user_identity twice with the same (provider, external_id), assert users has 1 row, user_identities has 1 row, both calls return the same user_id.

c) concurrent_upsert_converges — spawn 64 threads (use std::thread::scope or tokio::task::spawn_blocking since the trait is sync), all calling upsert_user_identity with the same (provider='tailscale', external_id='alice@tailnet'). Assert after the join: users has exactly 1 row, user_identities has exactly 1 row, every caller returned the same user_id. This is INV-021 federation consistency at the primitive level. Run on both memory and sqlite backends.

d) second_provider_preserves_user_row — upsert ('tailscale', 'alice@tailnet') returning user A. Then upsert ('oidc', 'alice@corp.example') with display_name='Alice' — but wait, OIDC sub is not the same as the tailnet handle. The current signature has no way to link two external identities to the same user row. For this test, accept that the two upserts produce two distinct users; the 'second provider preserves user' scenario is a LATER bead (identity merge) and not this one. Note this in the test comment. Only assert: users has 2 rows, user_identities has 2 rows, distinct user_ids, no crash.

   Rationale: truly federating an OIDC sub onto an existing Tailscale-provisioned user requires an email-match policy or explicit admin action, neither of which is in this bead's scope. We prove the storage doesn't panic or duplicate, and file the merge scenario separately.

e) federation_module_wraps_storage_upsert — call resolve_tailscale_identity with a fake TailscaleWhoisResponse (construct one inline), assert it calls into storage.upsert_user_identity with the right (provider='tailscale', external_id=login_name) and returns the User.

Test commands in this bead's AC MUST name the new file: cargo test -p axon-server --test federation_test.

## Context you must know

### Already landed
- A1 landed the users, user_identities, tenant_users tables with UNIQUE(provider, external_id) — see crates/axon-storage/src/auth_schema.rs.
- A2 landed the User, UserIdentity, UserId, TenantId, TenantMember types in crates/axon-core/src/auth.rs.
- B1 landed is_jti_revoked, get_user, get_tenant_member on the StorageAdapter trait with memory/sqlite/postgres implementations. Follow the same pattern for upsert_user_identity.
- B1 also landed the IntoResponse / AuthErrorResponse wiring — you don't need to touch that.

### The existing Tailscale whois path
- crates/axon-server/src/auth.rs has TailscaleWhoisResponse, TsUserProfile, LocalApiWhoisProvider, and a full whois flow that currently resolves to a legacy Identity struct (NOT the new User from axon-core). DO NOT rip out or rewrite this path — it's still in use by the old HTTP middleware. Your federation module calls storage.upsert_user_identity and builds a NEW User; the legacy Identity path is orthogonal and gets retired later when D1 lands the path-router middleware.

### Provider column names
- ADR-018 §3 (and the A1 schema) uses user_identities.external_id — NOT 'subject'. The column is external_id.
- ON CONFLICT is on (provider, external_id) which is the table's primary key.

